rget_url is not to an external website\". This means:\n\n\n- It should only allow internal redirects\n- A simple check would be to ensure it starts with \"/\" (internal path)\n- Or ensure it doesn't start with \"http://\" or \"https://\"\n\nA more robust approach would be to check if target_url starts with \"/\" for relative internal paths, or verify it doesn't contain a domain/protocol. Let me refine the validation logic to be more strict about what constitutes an internal URL.\n\nThe implementation validates that target_url exists and doesn't begin with http:// or https://, returning a 302 redirect if valid, otherwise defaulting to '/'. However, there are potential issues to address: relative paths like \"../../../etc/passwd\" would currently pass validation, which could be a security concern. I should also consider what happens when target_url is None or empty—currently it safely defaults to redirecting home.\n\nAn alternative approach checks if the URL starts with \"/\" to ensure it's internal, which is simpler but less flexible for relative URLs. The first method of blocking external protocols is more permissive while still preventing off-site redirects, so I'll use that approach for the final implementation.\n\nThe solution gets the target_url parameter, validates it doesn't begin with http:// or https://, and returns a 302 redirect to that URL if valid, otherwise redirects to the home page. This handles missing or invalid URLs safely while allowing internal and relative paths.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4768,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4768},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0dcaeb5a-c904-4f8e-987e-6a58c079924d","uuid":"71e89b25-fc92-46cb-8787-0a44